				\begin{document}$$\gamma = \frac{1}{{2A}}(E_{\mathrm{slab}} - n{\mu} _{\mathrm{mol}} - m{\mu} _{\mathrm{Pb}} - l{\mu} _I),$$\end{document}where Eslab is the total energy of the slab model with two surfaces, A is the surface area per unit cell, and each quantities satisfy the relations, μmol + μPb + 3μI = Ecubic for cubic phase and μmol + μPb + 3μI = 1/2Ehex for hexagonal phase. Among the high symmetry surfaces of cubic and hexagonal phase of FAPbI3 investigated in this study, the (111) surface of cubic FAPbI3 and (001) surface of hexagonal FAPbI3 have the highest surface energies (see Fig. 2) with the energy close to ~6 eV/nm2.
